/home/sean/.hermes/skills/devops/hermes-memory-architecture/SKILL.md:100:- **OpenClaw has its own memory layer too — it's not the same as Hermes' memory.** When `~/.openclaw/agents/<id>/<id>/` ships with an `active-memory` extension (or any `memory-core` plugin), OpenClaw registers its own `memory_search` and `memory_get` tools inside the OpenClaw session. Those are NOT visible to Hermes and are NOT what `session_search` queries. If a user mentions "I asked OpenClaw about my preferences last week" the right retrieval path is to start an OpenClaw session, not to call `session_search` in Hermes. The two systems have isolated session DBs, isolated memory files, and isolated tool registries. The user's `~/.openclaw/identity/device-auth.json` and `~/.hermes/identity/` are also separate.
/home/sean/.hermes/skills/devops/hermes-memory-architecture/SKILL.md:166:- **Cleaning up a broken frontend must never touch the working frontend's processes or data.** The EKKOLearnAI web form and the EKKOLearnAI desktop form **share a data dir (`~/.hermes-web-ui/`) and a bridge binary path** (`hermes-web-ui/dist/server/agent-bridge/hermes_bridge.py` is loaded by both). The web form's bridge uses `--endpoint ipc:///tmp/hermes-agent-bridge.sock`; the Studio desktop form's bridge uses `--endpoint tcp://127.0.0.1:<port>`. Same binary, different process, different endpoint — you cannot blanket-`pkill -f hermes_bridge.py` without inspecting the `--endpoint` flag first. The web form's data dir (`hermes-web-ui.db`, `.token`, `.login-lock.json`, `logs/`) must survive any Studio desktop cleanup; the `~/.config/hermes-studio/` Electron user-data dir is safe to delete because it belongs to the desktop form's GUI window (the web form has no Electron). The user explicitly stated this guardrail in 2026-06-11 ("同意先卸载Studio的desktop app, 不要错误删除web ui"). Treat the per-path ownership table in `references/studio-desktop-uninstall-recipe-2026-06-11.md` as the source of truth for what stays and what goes. **Tested pattern**: list all PIDs in two columns (web form — keep, Studio — kill) BEFORE any `kill`, verify Web UI is still HTTP 200 BEFORE deleting any file, and verify the Web UI is still HTTP 200 AGAIN at the end of the cleanup. The Web UI is the user's working frontend; if it goes down, the cleanup is broken even if the disk targets were all hit correctly.
